**Method 1 (Change the limits).** Let $u = x^2 + 1$, so 
$du = 2x\dx$. When $x = 0$, $u = 0^2 + 1 = 1$. When $x = 1$, 
$u = 1^2 + 1 = 2$. Therefore
\[
 \defint{0}{1} 2x\,(x^2 + 1)^5\dx 
 = \defint{1}{2} u^5\,du 
 = \frac{u^6}{6}\bigg\rvert_{1}^{2} 
 = \frac{64}{6} - \frac{1}{6} 
 = \frac{63}{6} 
 = \frac{21}{2}.
\]

**Method 2 (Back-substitute).** From our earlier work, 
$\int 2x(x^2+1)^5\dx = \frac{(x^2+1)^6}{6} + C$. Thus
\[
 \defint{0}{1} 2x\,(x^2+1)^5\dx 
 = \frac{(x^2+1)^6}{6}\bigg\rvert_{0}^{1} 
 = \frac{2^6}{6} - \frac{1^6}{6} 
 = \frac{64 - 1}{6} 
 = \frac{21}{2}.
\]
Both methods give $\dfrac{21}{2}$, as they must.\;
